President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation designating September 6-8, 2013, as National Days of Prayer and Remembrance in honor of the victims of the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks. In the proclamation, Obama reflects on the 12th anniversary of the attacks and pays tribute to the first responders, passengers and crew of Flight 93, and the men and women in the Armed Forces who have served and sacrificed since 9/11. He encourages the American people to honor and remember the victims through prayer, contemplation, memorial services, visiting memorials, ringing bells, candlelight vigils, and other appropriate activities. The president also extends an invitation for people around the world to participate in this commemoration.